CMSC320: Introduction to Data Science - Final Tutorial - Analysis of Movie Dataset: Exploring Factors Affecting Movie Success and Predictive Modeling¶

Introduction¶

The world of movies has always captivated audiences, offering a glimpse into different worlds, emotions, and stories. With the advent of digital platforms and advancements in technology, the movie industry has experienced significant growth, leading to an explosion of movies being produced and consumed globally. Amidst this vast landscape of films, understanding the factors that contribute to a movie's success or failure becomes crucial for filmmakers, producers, and investors alike.

This tutorial aims to explore and analyze the IMDb movies database, a comprehensive collection of movie-related information, to gain insights into the various aspects that influence a movie's performance. By delving into this dataset, we seek to uncover patterns, trends, and relationships that can shed light on the factors behind a movie's success, such as ratings, genres, budgets, and more.

My personal interest in this analysis stems from my fascination with the magic of movies and the desire to unravel the underlying dynamics that shape their outcomes. By leveraging data science techniques, I will extract valuable information from this extensive movie database. This will enabling us to make informed decisions and predictions in the realm of filmmaking and entertainment.

The importance of this problem in the data science industry cannot be understated. The movie industry is highly competitive, with filmmakers and production companies constantly striving to create films that resonate with audiences and generate substantial returns on investment. By leveraging data-driven insights, industry professionals can make informed decisions about which genres to explore, how to allocate budgets effectively, and which elements to prioritize in their productions. Additionally, understanding the preferences and expectations of moviegoers can contribute to the creation of more engaging and captivating films.

Coulumn heading and their description -¶

  • color: Indicates whether the movie is in color or black and white.
  • director_name: The name of the director of the movie.
  • num_critic_for_reviews: The number of critic reviews for the movie.
  • duration: The duration of the movie in minutes.
  • director_facebook_likes: The number of Facebook likes for the director.
  • actor_3_facebook_likes: The number of Facebook likes for the third actor in the movie.
  • actor_2_name: The name of the second actor in the movie.
  • actor_1_facebook_likes: The number of Facebook likes for the first actor in the movie.
  • gross: The gross earnings of the movie.
  • genres: The genres of the movie (e.g., action, drama, comedy).
  • actor_1_name: The name of the first actor in the movie.
  • movie_title: The title of the movie.
  • num_voted_users: The number of users who voted for the movie on IMDB.
  • cast_total_facebook_likes: The total number of Facebook likes for all actors in the movie.
  • actor_3_name: The name of the third actor in the movie.
  • facenumber_in_poster: The number of faces visible on the movie poster.
  • plot_keywords: Keywords associated with the movie's plot.
  • movie_imdb_link: The IMDB link for the movie.
  • num_user_for_reviews: The number of user reviews for the movie.
  • language: The language of the movie.
  • country: The country where the movie was produced.
  • content_rating: The content rating of the movie (e.g., PG-13, R, G).
  • budget: The budget of the movie.
  • title_year: The year when the movie was released.
  • actor_2_facebook_likes: The number of Facebook likes for the second actor in the movie.
  • imdb_score: The IMDB rating score for the movie.
  • aspect_ratio: The aspect ratio of the movie.
  • movie_facebook_likes: The number of Facebook likes for the movie's Facebook page.

This dataset contains 28 variables for 5043 movies spanning across 100 years in 66 countries. There are 2399 unique director names, and thousands of actors/actresses.

Exploratory Data Analysis¶

The Exploratory Data Analysis (EDA) is an essential step in understanding and gaining insights from the IMDB Movie dataset. By examining various aspects of the data, we can uncover patterns, trends, and relationships that exist within the dataset. The EDA helps us to explore the characteristics of the movies, such as language, country, genre, and their impact on factors like gross revenue, profitability, and audience engagement.

The EDA begins by analyzing the number of movies in different languages and countries, providing insights into the distribution and prevalence of movies across different linguistic and geographical regions. We then delve into understanding the movie production trends over time by examining the count of movies released each year. This allows us to identify periods of high or low movie production and observe any notable changes in the industry. Furthermore, we examine the impact of directors on movie success by analyzing the gross revenue of the top 10 directors. This enables us to recognize influential directors who have contributed significantly to the industry's financial success.

Next, we explore the profitability of movies by examining the profit versus budget for the top 20 most profitable movies. This analysis provides insights into the financial success of movies and their return on investment. We then investigate the relationship between movie ratings (IMDB scores) and financial performance, by examining the correlation between IMDB scores and factors such as gross revenue, profitability, and Facebook likes.

Finally, we consider the relationship between IMDB scores and the year of movie release. By applying linear regression, we can identify any trends or patterns in movie ratings over time, helping us understand the evolving tastes and preferences of the audience.

Relationship between number of movies and language¶

Movies are not only a form of entertainment but also a powerful medium for cultural expression. Analyzing the number of movies for each language helps us understand which languages are being utilized to represent and preserve different cultures on screen. It highlights the efforts made to showcase diverse narratives, perspectives, and experiences from around the world.

Relation between Genre and Movie Production¶

Examining the relationship between genre and movie production provides valuable market analysis. By identifying trends and patterns in genre popularity, industry stakeholders can make informed decisions about investments, marketing strategies, and distribution channels. Hypothesis Testing¶

In this hypothesis testing, we aim to investigate the proportion of profitable movies in the dataset. The null hypothesis (H0) states that 50% or less of the movies are profitable, while the alternative hypothesis (H1) suggests that more than 50% of the movies are profitable.

To calculate the proportion of profitable movies, we define a logical analogy for profitability: if the profit is greater than 0, the movie is considered profitable; otherwise, it is considered unprofitable.

Based on the previous graph that examined profits vs. budget for the top 20 movies, we observed that many movies with smaller budgets still ranked among the most profitable. This observation forms the basis for our alternative hypothesis, as it suggests that a significant portion of movies can be profitable despite lower budgets.

By conducting hypothesis testing, we can evaluate the evidence and determine whether there is sufficient support to reject the null hypothesis in favor of the alternative hypothesis.

In [ ]:
# Add the 'profitable' column
data['Profitable'] = np.where(data['Profit'] > 0, True, False)

# Calculate the number of profitable and unprofitable movies
profitable_count = data['Profitable'].sum()
total_count = len(data)

# Calculating p_hat (proportion of profitable movies)
p_hat = profitable_count / total_count

# Set the significance level
alpha = 0.05

# Perform the hypothesis test
z_stat, p_value = proportions_ztest(profitable_count, total_count, value=0.5)

# Evaluate the p-value
if p_value <= alpha:
    print(p_value)
    print(p_hat)
    print("Reject the null hypothesis")
else:
    print(p_value)
    print(p_hat)
    print("Fail to reject the null hypothesis")

4.642087620790794e-13
0.5533553355335533
Reject the null hypothesis

The result of the hypothesis testing suggests that we have sufficient evidence to reject the null hypothesis, which stated that 50% or less of the movies are profitable.

Based on the dataset, the proportion of profitable movies (p_hat) is calculated to be approximately 0.5534, indicating that more than 55% of the movies are profitable.

The hypothesis test was performed using a significance level (alpha) of 0.05. The resulting p-value is extremely small (approximately 4.64e-13), which is significantly smaller than the significance level. Therefore, we reject the null hypothesis in favor of the alternative hypothesis, which states that more than 50% of the movies are profitable.

This implies that the dataset provides strong evidence that a significant portion of movies are profitable, contradicting the assumption that profitability is limited to 50% or less of the movies. The findings support the hypothesis that movies can be financially successful, even if they have lower budgets, as seen in the previous analysis of profits vs. budgets.

Linear Regression Model¶

In this analysis, we aim to explore the relationship between the IMDb score and the year of release for movies. To investigate this relationship, we will employ a linear regression model. The objective is to determine if there is a significant relationship between the IMDb score and the year of release.

The null hypothesis (H0) in this case assumes that there is no relationship between the IMDb score and the year of release. In other words, the IMDb score is not influenced by the year in which a movie is released.

To focus our analysis on movies released after 1990, we will filter the dataset to include only movies released from the year 2000 onwards. This allows us to examine the relationship between the IMDb score and the year of release specifically within the context of recent movies.

By fitting the linear regression model and conducting appropriate statistical tests, we can evaluate whether there is evidence to reject the null hypothesis and conclude that a relationship exists between the IMDb score and the year of release for movies.

In [ ]:
# Filter the data for movies released from 2000 to 2017
filtered_data = data[(data['Year'] >= 1990) & (data['Year'] <= 2017)]

# Prepare the data for regression analysis

# Add a constant term to the predictor variable
X = sm.add_constant(X)

# Fit the linear regression model

# Print the summary of the model

The linear regression analysis between the IMDb score and the year of release for movies from 1990 to 2017 reveals the following results:

R-squared: The R-squared value of 0.005 indicates that approximately 0.5% of the variability in the IMDb score can be explained by the year of release. This suggests that the year of release has a very weak, but statistically significant, association with the IMDb score.

Year coefficient: The coefficient for the predictor variable "Year" is -0.0126. This means that, on average, there is a small decrease (-0.0126) in the IMDb score per unit increase in the year of release. The coefficient is statistically significant, as indicated by the p-value (P>|t|) of 0.

Overall, the linear regression model shows a very weak negative relationship between the IMDb score and the year of release for movies from 1990 to 2017. The R-squared value suggests that there are other factors beyond the year of release that have a more substantial influence on the IMDb score. However, the statistically significant coefficient for the "Year" variable indicates that there is a small but meaningful relationship between the two.

Therefore, based on the analysis, we can conclude that the year of release has a weak negative association with the IMDb score for movies released from 1990 to 2017.

The residuals are symmetrically distributed around the zero line (residual = 0). This symmetry indicates that, on average, the model's predictions are close to the actual IMDb scores, and there is no systematic bias or trend in the residuals.

The height and shape of the violin at each year indicate the density of residuals for that particular year. A taller and wider violin indicates a higher density of residuals, suggesting more variability in the IMDb scores for that year. Conversely, a shorter and narrower violin represents a lower density of residuals and less variability in the IMDb scores.

Spitting the data (Testing and Training set)¶

In this section, we split the prepared dataset into two subsets: training data and test data. This is a crucial step in evaluating the performance and generalization ability of the classification models.

The purpose of splitting the data is to have a portion of the dataset that is not used during model training, which can later be used to evaluate the model's performance on unseen data. The training data is used to train the models, allowing them to learn patterns and relationships in the data, while the test data serves as a benchmark to assess how well the models generalize to new observations.

In [ ]:
X=pd.DataFrame(columns=['duration','director_facebook_likes','actor_1_facebook_likes','gross','num_voted_users','facenumber_in_poster','budget','title_year','aspect_ratio','movie_facebook_likes','Other_actor_facebbok_likes','critic_review_ratio','country_USA','country_other','content_rating_G','content_rating_GP','content_rating_M','content_rating_NC-17','content_rating_Not Rated','content_rating_PG','content_rating_PG-13','content_rating_Passed','content_rating_R','content_rating_TV-14','content_rating_TV-G','content_rating_TV-PG','content_rating_Unrated','content_rating_X'],data=data2)

X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test=train_test_split(X,y,test_size=0.3,random_state=100)

The commonly used approach for splitting the data is the train-test split, where a certain percentage of the data is allocated for training and the remaining percentage is reserved for testing. In our case, we allocate 70% of the data for training and 30% for testing, as specified by the test_size=0.3 parameter in the train_test_split function.

By splitting the data, we can evaluate the performance metrics, such as accuracy, precision, recall, and F1-score, on the test data to assess how well the models are able to classify the IMDb scores of movies. This evaluation provides insights into the models' ability to generalize to unseen data and helps in selecting the best-performing model for our prediction task.

KNN Clasifier¶

We transform the test data (X_test) using the already fitted imputer. The transform method fills in the missing values in X_test with the respective means learned from the training data, producing X_test_imputed.

We create a KNN classifier with n_neighbors set to 22 and fit it on the imputed training data (X_train_imputed) and corresponding labels (y_train). The classifier learns the patterns and relationships in the data.

We then predict on the imputed test data (X_test_imputed) using the fitted KNN classifier. The predicted values are stored in knnpred. We calculate the confusion matrix using metrics.confusion_matrix to evaluate the performance of the classifier. The confusion matrix shows the number of true positives, true negatives, false positives, and false negatives for each class. Additionally, we calculate the accuracy score using metrics.accuracy_score, which provides the overall accuracy of the classifier.

# Create an instance of the SimpleImputer with desired strategy

Support Vector Classifier (SVC)¶

We utilize the SVC algorithm for classification. We transform both the training and test data (X_train and X_test) using the fitted imputer. This replaces any missing values in the datasets with the corresponding mean values learned from the training data. The transformed data is stored in X_train_imputed and X_test_imputed, respectively.

We create an instance of SVC with the desired kernel, in this case, 'sigmoid'. The SVC model will be trained using the imputed training data.

We fit the SVC model on the imputed training data (X_train_imputed) and the corresponding labels (y_train) using the fit method. The model learns the patterns and relationships in the data.

Next, we use the trained model to predict on the imputed test data (X_test_imputed) and store the predicted values in svcpred.

We calculate the confusion matrix using metrics.confusion_matrix to evaluate the performance of the classifier. The confusion matrix provides insights into the number of true positives, true negatives, false positives, and false negatives for each class.

Finally, we calculate the accuracy score using metrics.accuracy_score, which gives the overall accuracy of the classifier in predicting the correct class labels.

#SVC

# Create an instance of SimpleImputer to handle missing values
imputer = SimpleImputer(strategy='mean')

# Fit the imputer on X_train to learn the mean values for imputation
imputer.fit(X_train)

# Transform X_train and X_test to replace the missing values with the learned mean values
X_train_imputed = imputer.transform(X_train)
X_test_imputed = imputer.transform(X_test)

# Create an instance of SVC with the desired kernel
svc = SVC(kernel='sigmoid')

# Fit the SVC model on the imputed training data
svc.fit(X_train_imputed, np.ravel(y_train, order='C'))

# Predict on the imputed test data
svcpred = svc.predict(X_test_imputed)

# Calculate and print the confusion matrix
cnf_matrix = metrics.confusion_matrix(y_test, svcpred)
print(cnf_matrix)

# Calculate and print the accuracy score
accuracy = metrics.accuracy_score(y_test, svcpred)

The obtained confusion matrix suggests that the classifier's performance varies across different classes. The overall accuracy of 55.56% indicates that the classifier correctly predicts the class labels for approximately 55.56% of the instances in the test data.

Random Forest Classifier¶

We create an instance of RandomForestClassifier from sklearn.ensemble with the desired number of estimators (200 in this case). RandomForestClassifier is an ensemble algorithm that combines multiple decision trees to make predictions.It can handle both classification and regression tasks and is known for its robustness and ability to handle complex relationships in the data. We fit the RandomForestClassifier model on the imputed training data (X_train_imputed) and the corresponding target labels (y_train). The model learns the patterns and relationships in the data to make predictions. Next, we transform the test data (X_test) using the same imputer to replace missing values with the learned mean values. We then use the trained RandomForestClassifier to predict the labels for the imputed test data.

# Create an instance of SimpleImputer to handle missing values

Conclusion¶

Recap:¶

The purpose of this project was to analyze a movie dataset and explore various factors such as the number of movies, year of release, budget, profit, gross, language, genres, directors, and more. Through exploratory data analysis (EDA) and data prediction using classification models, we aimed to gain insights into the movie industry and understand the relationships between different variables.

During the EDA phase, we made several observations. We found that English-language movies dominated the dataset, with the highest number of movies produced in the USA. The number of movies showed an increasing trend over the years. Drama and comedy were the most prevalent genres. We also explored the relationship between top directors and movie gross, identified the top 20 most profitable movies, and observed positive correlations between IMDB scores and gross, Facebook likes, and profit. Our hypothesis testing confirmed that movies, in general, are more profitable.

In the data prediction phase, we compared the performance of three classification models: K-Nearest Neighbors (KNN), Support Vector Classifier (SVC), and Random Forest Classifier. KNN achieved an accuracy of approximately 66.24%, SVC achieved an accuracy of approximately 55.56%, and Random Forest Classifier outperformed the others with an accuracy of approximately 68.07%. We employed mean imputation to handle missing values in the dataset, which improved the performance of the models.

Future Scope of data analysis:¶

Looking ahead, there are several avenues for future analysis. Firstly, incorporating additional variables such as actors, production companies, and release regions could provide deeper insights into the movie industry. Furthermore, fine-tuning the hyperparameters of the classification models and exploring other evaluation metrics like precision, recall, and F1-score would enhance the model assessment. Additionally, conducting sentiment analysis on user reviews or utilizing natural language processing techniques could provide a more comprehensive understanding of the factors influencing movie success.

Limitations:¶

This project has certain limitations. The dataset used may not represent the entire movie industry, as it is based on a specific dataset with its own biases and limitations. Additionally, the accuracy of the classification models may be influenced by the quality and representativeness of the features used for prediction. Moreover, the conclusions drawn are based on the data available up until the project's knowledge cutoff in 2017.
